Laundry is the thing I hate most about college.  Not papers.  Not tests.  Laundry.  I always have so many clothes to wash; there are barely enough washers; there are never any dryers; people leave their crap in the washers and dryers for long periods of time even after they are finished; the room is dark and isolated and depressing; and I HATE IT!

I am going to rugby practice tonight.  I hope that I have time to keep up with this.  I want to destroy people on the pitch!  Can you imagine that?  Me, tackling other girls in an effort to win a game?  I love it!  I'm not fierce.

Ben Folds was FANTASTIC!  Expect pictures when I can get my snapfish account to work again.

Summer job update...

Day Camp Counselor at the YMCA...  I really do love this job.  It's frustrating.  The days are long.  The kids are spoiled.  I only liked about half of the people I worked with... but I still loved it.  I am so proud to say that I took care of kids all summer.  I was a pleasant addition to their daily life, and I made the summer a bit less monotonous for kids that had no where else to go every day.  Last summer I had a group of 7 & 8 year old boys, who nearly killed me.  However, this summer I had somewhere between 15 and 20 7 & 8 year old girls in my group every day, and I loved them.  They were fun and goofy and kind and really liked me, which made life so much easier.  My favorite camp story (which many have already heard, but it is so good I must share)... I was sitting with one of my campers in my lap just talking to her.  She gropes me and says "Boobies boobies!"  After I asked her why she did that she said "Well, I do it to my mom all the time."  *sigh*  Kids are so silly.

 

Actually I don't really have anything else to say about the summer now... It was wonderful, and I dont' really feel the need to reminisce now.  I loved every second of it...

 

Now to Vandy news.

 

Move in went well.  I have my car, thank goodness.  I don't need it too often, but it is so nice to know that it is right there if I do need it.

I am living in the coolest place, ever!  I live in a Mayfield, which is a living learning house on campus.  Essentially what you do is have some sort of learning or service project throughout the year and you get to live in a house on campus.  Our project is basically women's studies.  We haven't started yet, and it will be an obligation, but a cool experience at the same time I'm sure.  10 people live in a two story house with 10 (really small) single rooms, two bathrooms, a common room, and a kitchen (hallway).  I love the people I live with so much too.  The whole upstairs is in theatre, and we rock the world.  Any Mayfield nickname ideas may be submitted in comment form to this entry (so far we have MF9 and GIOIP... prounounced gee-oip).  I love leaving my door open to these people.  They are so kind and funny and welcoming.  My house makes me so happy!  AHHHHH!!!

 

Classes seem to be good.  I'm taking 2 psci classes, my potential major.  I am so excited.  I love the subject.  I am a nerd.  Also, Spanish, a possible minor.  Then acting... I'm so excited about acting.  I know and love so many people in the class, and at this point it looks like the majority of the class will be acting exercises and games.  My other class is ethics, which is great!  There is a rumor that my ethics professor inspired Robin Williams character in Dead Poet's Society, and after having two of his classes, I believe it.  It is so inspiring to see such a ridiculously interesting person.  When the hour of class ends, few people seem to want to leave.  My schedule is also great because it will not include so many hard science classes.  An easier more interesting schedule sounds great to me.

 

I loved this summer so much, but I am happier to be back at VU than I ever could have imagined.  I am so lucky to have found so many close friends in such a short period of time.  YAY!

 

VUT.  I love VUT.  Thank God for theatre.  I would be missing so much in my life without this organization.  They have had two parties (one of which Eric Kacker went to... hmm).  I'm almost proud of the fact that the second party of the year was shut down.  It shows how determined an organization we are!  Way to go guys.  Umm... I didn't make either play.  It does really hurt, a lot.  I didn't think it would quite this much.  I didn't really expect a good part in Iphigenia (a Greek play by Euripides), I was hoping for something though.  I expected nothing in Company, and am not crushed.  I am not a singer and I realize that.  I would love to be though, so if anyone would like to donate a beautiful voice just let me know.  Yeah, but anything I would have been happy with.  I love to act.  I love to perform.  It really lightens up my mood (I know I'm obnoxiously happy already, maybe that's why I didn't get cast, so there are a few less YAYs said per day).  Honestly, nothing gives me more joy than being on stage, which is bizarre because I know I am not the best actress ever, but I adore performing so incredibly much.  At least I can choreograph for Momentum.  I will at least get to perform there this semester.  *cries a little*  Okay, self pity must end here.  I don't even know why I'm writing all this.  I must learn from my ethics class that although there is no pay off now, if I keep putting in effort and overall the pleasure will outweigh the pain.  I really will be fine.  I must get out my initial frustrations, and then I will be happy and love watching each of the shows over and over again because I really do cherish all that is VUT.

 

Now pictures that make me happy.

My home

 

My (and my spousy's) lover

You Know You're From Alabama When...
You have a party or a barbeque whenever Alabama plays Auburn in football. You go to Gulf Shores every summer. You call the Atlanta Braves baseball team "us" like they're actually from Alabama. You would much rather visit Florida than California. You don't "take", you "carry" or "tote"... as in "You want me to carry you down to the 7-11?" A soft drink isn't soda, cola, or pop, it's Coke. You call it a "buggy" and not a shopping cart. You've said "fixin' to," "might could," or "usetacould" during the last week. Someone you know has used a football schedule to plan their wedding date. You know the meaning of the phrase "Fobbed again." You can properly pronounce Eufaula, Opelika, Bayou La Batre, and Oneonta. The Talladega 500 is the biggest sporting event of any sort during the entire year. You know exactly what chitlins and mountain oysters are, and you know someone who eats them anyway. You think that people who complain about the humidity in other states are sissies. You aren't surprised to find rental movies, groceries, ammunition and bait all in the same store. You've missed a wedding or a funeral to go to a football game. Asian food is always "CHINESE" regardless of the fact that it may actually be Korean or Japanese or Thai You actually get these jokes and pass them on to other friends from Alabama.

You Know You're From Nashville When...
The word "snow" means a week off from school and maybe even work. To you Paris is near Waverly and Athens and Rome are in Georgia. You stop your car for ambulances, fire trucks and hearses. You take down your Christmas tree before January first. Someone within hearing distance is singing or humming. There's a musical instrument somewhere in the house. You don't do things without "fixin" to do them first. You judge things as "alright", "fine" or "right fine". Your food has beans or Tobasco in it. You know what a T-Rac is. You "luck up" and not "luck out". Drivers stop before they turn. Someone you know has written a song. You own the boots but can't ride a horse. No one around you is a native Nashvillian either. You run red lights so you won't be hit from behind. Fast food is faster inside than at the drive-up window. To you a well-trained dog stays in the bed of the truck. Half of the people at work know someone in entertainment. Strangers ask if you're doin alright, and friends ask what's goin on. You ignore country stars but dance and holler in front of football players. You actually get these jokes and pass them on to other friends from Nashville.

Home is good.  I am relaxed.  It's been a while since I've felt relaxed, but I really didn't mind that.  I was so stressed for classes and things at Vandy, but I honestly loved every minute of it.  Freshman year was truly fantastic.  I couldn't have made a better decision.  I couldn't have asked for more.  I really will post memories one of these days, just not today.  But thank you to all who made my freshman year at Vanderbilt perfect.

I'm going to be a political science major.  I have decided.  Who really knows if that will stand, but I really love the idea of doing something with a political science major because I'm really passionate about it.  So political science major with minors in Spanish and Theatre.  Sounds good to me.  I love that I am making decisions.  I am the most indecisive person in the world.  I am loving this!

I have emailed a bunch of lawyers around Birmingham that are Vandy allumni to see if they have any advice (or summer jobs).  No jobs, but lots of helpful people.  They all really want to help me know all I can.  This is good too.

I feel like I've hardly seen anyone since I've been home.  People need to get home and hang out with me!  I am relaxed though, and that is a beautiful feeling.  I've been sleeping so much, working out, watching TV, watching movies, eating my mom's yummy food, and I started this book called Exodus which is supposed to be great.

Today, I think I'll go shopping and work out.  A good day.

So, it looks like I will be a day camp counselor again this summer.  I don't mind.  I am so proud of that job.  It is hard but rewarding.  However lame that is, it really is.  I really feel good about what I do.  Hopefully, I will have a group of girls this summmer.  The bad thing is that I have training THIS WEEKEND.  So soon.  So I have to go to Camp Cosby for the weekend and play silly "Get to know you" games all weekend.  Bummer... hopefully my brother will go so I have someone that I like there to hang out with.

I don't have anything interesting to say.

I love the daily show.  Jon Stewart is my hero.

I can't believe what is going on in the world right now.  I am disgusted with so many things.  I don't really have anything else to say about that.  Actually I have a lot to say, but I don't want to say it on lj.  That's all.

I'm going to go now.  I love you all.

~laura

one of the things i'm most excited about doing this summer is choreographing something for momentum to do next fall.  i cannot wait.  i cannot decide either.  just about every song i listen to i want to choreograph soemthing.  i love dancing so very much... that is what i have been doing in my room since my last journal entry.  i should study chemistry... but alas, i will put it off for now.  i'm still recovering from biology... although the nap from 1-3:45 was pretty amazing too.

so which on of these sounds cool for momentum...
jet - are you gonna be my girl
Just a rocked out dance with some moves from the IPOD commercial.
outkast - the whole world
Fosse style, chic and hip hopefully.
kill bill - whistling song (twisted nerve)
A modern ballet kind of piece (hopefully hip with people doing very different things and coming together in the dramatic parts of the song).  This could either be amazing or just wrong.  I think it could be very cool if I got good dancers to do it.
last of the mohicans - theme
Modern/Lyrical I guess is what I would do with this one.
pulp ficion - miserlou
Edging on cheesy (but purposefully), sort of a jazzy/bouncy/60s dance party dancing something.
fosse - anything
I love Fosse.
white stripes - the hardest button to button
A jerky jazz/modern piece.  I was just inspired by this one.  There could be a cool build in this one.

Umm... yeah... I'd love to hear what you all think about these.  Not that any of you care... but I'm going to have to narrow it down sometime, and I'd love any ideas.  I think that my favorites are Kill Bill whistling, The Hardest Button to Button, and Are You Gonna Be My Girl.  I think that they have the potential for the most cool factor.  That's all.

i will be home in one week.  that is very exciting!  no stress for two or three months.  how beautiful.  but it's also sad.  my freshman year has been amazing.  i could not have loved it more.  thank you to all who have made it fantastic.  scales, vut (banquet was amazing!), momentum, everything.  i have loved (practically) every moment of this year.  i could not be in a better place in my life right now.  to be this happy the day before the hardest test i have probably ever had to take in my life... that's pretty impressive.  YAY VANDERBILT!

at the same time, summer is necessary right now.  i can't wait to see all of you at home.  i love you so much.  this summer is going to be incredible (it better be!)!  EEK!!!  fun times will be had.

okay, i need to study again now.  we'll see how this goes.  YIKES BIOLOGY!

have a fantastic day!

~laura

i feel the need to leave you all with something great if i am to write this lj post.  i don't know what though.

how about this.  i was proud of myself.
i had to do an oral presentation in my spanish class today.  my group presented on spain, and i decided to do my part on el teatro de espana.  i wanted to have some video clip or something to take up time... so i found a couple spanish plays in the library; picked out a good melodramatic monologue; and made a video of myself reading it.  it was extremely cheesy, purposefully so.  i had the godfather theme music playing in the background, and i was ridiculously dramatic, and it was obvious that it was me turning the camera on and off , and i had opening credits (which was just me holding up a piece of paper at the beginning).  so i prefaced this by saying that i found an authentic spanish monologue by a famous spanish actress.  then i played my movie.  i was very happy, and the class laughed, so i guess it was a success.

so... YAY ICON!

random story...

so i went to the rec with my friends elizabeth and jake.  we are walking back to our dorms afterward, and we find a nice grassy hill so, naturally, we decided to lay down on it.  this random guy (i assume that he was homeless) walks by and mumbles something.  i look away because he was creepy and then he turns to jake and mubles some random stuff.  he eventually said "you know what i've been through man.  you don't know the stuff i've seen.  do you know where i've been?"  jake being a good boy responded, allowing elizabeth and i to look away, "where have you been?"  he responded "vietnam man."  he mumbles stuff about bullets and whatever and makes arm movements to signifying the bullets i assume.  and he turns to jake and says "you think this is a joke man?"  jake says "no sir, thank you for what you did."  by the way, he wasn't indimidating... he was a little guy.  and then he says, "you're just sitting out here with these two babes, and you think this is a joke.  it's not fair, man.  and the red head man (i didn't realize i was a red head), i like red heads."  then jake said something about needing to study, so we get up to leave.  and the guy says "just remember man.  *insert movements of a man holding a rifle and shooting and making weak pow pow pow noises* remember man."  we then walked away quickly.

so, it was funny i guess.  it was just really random and bizarre.  i must admit i do feel bad for the guy, but i was very anxious to get away.  and then i laughed (i felt bad, but i laughed anyway).

end of story.

that was random and didn't come out funny or anything like i thought it would.  or maybe it did.  der.

THEATRE BANQUET IS TOMORROW!!!!!!!!!!!  EEK!!!

now end of story.

i am addicted. very much so.

Marriage is love.

so after taking a biology test on monday last night i stayed up really late working on various assignments, only to wake up once again at 7:50 for my 8:10 class.  tonight i am still awake now because i have a political science presentation on italy tomorrow.  i think it will go well, but i basically didn't get a chance to start until early today.  and then friday, no later than 8 am i have to turn in a 7 to 10 page research paper on how the masculinity of a country (spain, poland, and brazil to be exact) affects the perception of gays.  i came up with the topic myself.  its obscurity is just me shooting myself in the foot.  i have basically done all of the research for it (although i'm sure that i will find holes tomorrow... but i'm having a hard time finding where else to look).  now i just have to prove something.  it is hard to prove something when your data on all three countries is about the same.
